comment: LATR and R-Slash show Gasol (CHI) blocks the ball prior to any contact with Dudley's (MIL) arm and the contact is considered incidental after the blocked shot occurs.
Rose (CHI) cleanly blocks Henson's (MIL) dunk attempt.
Dudley (MIL) does not catch the pass cleanly and the ball hitting the ground on the dropped pass does not constitute a dribble.
Mirotic (CHI) makes incidental contact after Dudley (MIL) has already released the ball on his layup attempt.
Henson (MIL) reaches in from behind and makes contact with Gasol (CHI) that causes him to lose control of the ball.
Dudley (MIL) makes contact with Gasol's (CHI) body and the contact affects his movement to the basket during his layup attempt.
Noah (CHI) and Henson (MIL) briefly engage away from the ball.
Rose (CHI) makes contact with Bayless' (MIL) body while he is airborne and the contact affects his movement to the basket and layup attempt.
LHH shows that Middleton (MIL) makes contact with the ball and causes Gibson (CHI) to lose control of it.
Bayless (MIL) maintains legal guarding position and does not affect Rose's (CHI) RSBQ on his drive.
Middleton (MIL) does not intentionally kick the ball on the play.
Rose (CHI) has already lost control of the ball when Dudley (MIL) makes incidental body to body contact with him.

Coach Jason Kidd (MIL) is granted a timeout immediately after Middleton (MIL) secures possession. The game clock continues to run after the timeout and is correctly reset to 00:01.3. Milwaukee elects to use a 2nd timeout in order to advance the ball.
Rose (CHI) makes incidental contact with Bayless (MIL) after the ball has been released on his layup attempt.
After communicating with the Replay Center, the ruling on the court that Bayless (MIL) released the ball prior to the game clock expiring was upheld.
